article.description: Elena Baranova scored 19 points to lead the New York Liberty to a 75-58 triumph over the Charlotte Sting on Sunday.
article.headline: Liberty led by as many as 21in second half
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- After a rough stretch, the New York Liberty had
their most dominant game of the season.

Elena Baranova had 19 points and Crystal Robinson added 14 to
lead the New York Liberty to a 75-58 win over the Charlotte Sting
on Sunday.

"We had a lot of people do a lot of good things tonight," New
York interim coach Pat Coyle said. "This is the kind of effort we
need from here on out."

Becky Hammon had 12 points, six rebounds and six assists for the
Liberty, who shot a season-high 50 percent from the field. DeTrina
White had a team-high seven rebounds in 13 minutes.

The Liberty won for the third time in five games but just the
fourth in 14 since opening the season 6-1. New York is in a
three-way tie for fourth in the Eastern Conference, just two games
behind leader Indiana and one behind second-place Charlotte.

"We've never been more than 2½ games out of first place,"
Coyle said. "We're right in the thick of things. We just need to
continue to execute, play tough defense and we'll be fine."

New York went 8-for-18 from beyond the arc, led by Robinson's
4-for-7 shooting. The Liberty outscored the Sting 32-20 in the
paint and was their largest margin of victory since a 71-54 win at
Cleveland last Aug. 17.

Tammy Sutton-Brown led the Sting with 14 points and nine
rebounds, and Dawn Staley and rookie Kelly Mazzante added 11 points
apiece.

The Sting, who host the Liberty on Tuesday night, lost for just
the fourth time in 12 games. It was Charlotte's biggest loss since
a 69-48 defeat at Indiana on Aug. 3, 2002.

"New York came out and played very focused," Charlotte coach
Trudi Lacey said. "We made the same defensive mistakes over and
over. Our defense was very poor."

The Liberty led 40-31 at the break, and had a 13-0 run early in
the second half to take a 20-point lead. Charlotte then scored
eight straight points as part of a 12-3 run to cut the deficit to
58-47, but that was the closest margin.

"Once they get into a flow and feed off each other, it's hard
to get them out of their comfort zone," Staley said.

La'Keisha Frett, who played 10 games for Charlotte earlier in
the season, made her first start for the Liberty and scored eight
points in 15 minutes.

New York played its last game at Madison Square Garden before
returning for the season finale on Sept. 19. The Liberty will play
their next six home games at Radio City Music Hall to make way for
the Republican National Convention.
